IFAKARA Innovation Hub has offered some 15,000 US dollars (34m/-) to five groups of entrepreneurs to assist them turn their business creativity ideas into reality. The five groups sponsored to develop further their business ideas in area of producing alternative charcoal using solid waste, fish foods, poultry feeds, and making rice wine and medical devices. The Ifakara Innovation Hub acting Director, Mr Masoud Mnonji, said the groups were given between 300 US dollars and 5,000 US dollars to support their creative ideas. "Ifakara Innovation Hub has been supporting different designers, including medical device designers, as well as supporting the development of human resources," said Mr Mnonji when welcoming innovators to the single-day innovation symposium for medical devices that will be held at Costech ground in Dar es Salaam today. Mnonji said the single-day symposium geared to offer to the participants a platform to exchange knowledge and identifying the gaps in policies facing the innovators in the country. He also said the fish food processing group has been successful in finding their product markets in the country. "Also for instance the group of 10 young people who are engaged in rice cultivation in the Morogoro have successfully developed wine out of rice," said Mr Mnonji. For group making medical device managed to create incubators for premature babies on top of that have come with a production-method to create affordable female sanitation towels. "Ifakara Innovation Hub through funding from the Swiss Embassy in Tanzania, Ifakara, Health Institute and the Bontar Foundation has been at the forefront in supporting various innovators in the country," said Mr Mnonji.